<div id="review_480093181" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/480093181" />
    <a title="J.Elle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/208599-j-elle"><img alt="J.Elle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616384876p2/208599.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/480093181?book_show_action=true">Dec 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.Elle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.Elle" href="/user/show/208599-j-elle">J.Elle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer480093181" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12962647867008206657">This book seemed much better suited to a teen boy than a mom like me. So, teen boys, take notice, if you like reading books about supernatural beings, such as vampires (oh, I’m sorry, hemovores) you might like this. <br/><br/>Okay, who else had trouble with the whole hemovore/omnivore thing? Obviously, I could figure out what the difference was quickly based on dialogue in the book (even though it wasn’t addressed officially until far into things), but it irritated me that it wasn’t explained better much </span>
  <span id="freeText12962647867008206657" style="display:none">This book seemed much better suited to a teen boy than a mom like me. So, teen boys, take notice, if you like reading books about supernatural beings, such as vampires (oh, I’m sorry, hemovores) you might like this. <br /><br />Okay, who else had trouble with the whole hemovore/omnivore thing? Obviously, I could figure out what the difference was quickly based on dialogue in the book (even though it wasn’t addressed officially until far into things), but it irritated me that it wasn’t explained better much sooner. Am I just too old that I’ve forgotten small details from high school science? Should I have known what the definition of an omnivore was and then inferred what a hemovore was from that? You tell me. Then, there was the small matter of keeping them straight. Finally, I just told myself that since omnivore started with ‘o’, it stood for “only”, as in, “only human” and that settled that matter. Bored? Sorry. <br /><br />So, Cole is an ancient and super cautious hemovore. As weird as this will seem, I could relate to him. Not the whole needing to drink blood thing, but he always had a plan and he was prepared for everything. I’m one of those women who can pull anything someone might need from her purse. I’m always reminded of the movie <a href="http://http//www.imdb.com/title/tt0117247/" rel="nofollow noopener">One Fine Day</a> when Michelle Pfeiffer goes to drop the kids off at daycare and it’s a dress-up day and from her purse, she cobbles together two awesome outfits for her son and the girl from his class. I could TOTALLY do that. Anyway, I digress. One of Cole’s friends (Sandor) has accidentally created another hemovore, Gordon, and the unofficial head of their clan asks Cole and Sandor to go on the road with Gordon and show him the ropes. What follows is the vampire equivalent of a roadtrip.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12962647867008206657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


