<div id="review_40549104" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/40549104" />
    <a title="Lucy " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45923-lucy"><img alt="Lucy " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1300985055p2/45923.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/40549104?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lucy " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lucy " href="/user/show/45923-lucy">Lucy </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45923-lucy?shelf=teen">teen</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45923-lucy?shelf=vampires">vampires</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer40549104" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16005313332517212088">Cole looks like he&apos;s eighteen, but he&apos;s been eighteen for over a hundred years. He&apos;s wise and wary and knows how to take care of himself. Which is why he&apos;s a perfect candidate to help tutor Gordon, a new heme. Gordon is actually eighteen, and he has not yet accepted the realities of his new existence. Cole knows that he has to make Gordon understand what it means to live as a heme--to live forever, never aging, subsisting off the blood of omnis--and he also knows that if he can&apos;t, then Gordon wi</span>
  <span id="freeText16005313332517212088" style="display:none">Cole looks like he's eighteen, but he's been eighteen for over a hundred years. He's wise and wary and knows how to take care of himself. Which is why he's a perfect candidate to help tutor Gordon, a new heme. Gordon is actually eighteen, and he has not yet accepted the realities of his new existence. Cole knows that he has to make Gordon understand what it means to live as a heme--to live forever, never aging, subsisting off the blood of omnis--and he also knows that if he can't, then Gordon will be a danger to all hemes, and he will have to put him down. Cole doesn't want it to come to that. But Gordon doesn't seem to understand the stakes that are involved.<br /><br />AM Jenkins' hemes and their society--the Colony, the Building--are all fascinating to me, and I wish she'd spent more time exploring them. I wanted more of the heme dynamic--Johnny's enigmatic leadership, Frederick's obsession with the same topic forever, Mitch and his tongue stud--but instead we got a whole lot of Cole's hundred-year-old angst, which was way less interesting and got old fairly quickly.<br /><br />It felt like we were just skimming the surface of everything that made these books enticing.<br /><br />I hope AM Jenkins writes another heme novel, and I hope that that one instead focuses on some of the more interesting hemes--even a novel that centers around Sandor would be nice--and I hope it goes deeper into heme society as it relates to the vampire myth.<br /><br />There was so much that could have been done here--and none of the potential was realized.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16005313332517212088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


